<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="118" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="118">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="118">(Fig. 20). Nearctic: California, Idaho, Nevada, Oregon, Utah, Washington (USA); British Columbia (Canada).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="118" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="118">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="15" pageNumber="118">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Eulonchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eulonchus sapphirinus" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sapphirinus">Eulonchus sapphirinus</taxonomicName>
has been recorded visiting the flowers of 19 different plant families and 30 different species (Table 2). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Eulonchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eulonchus sapphirinus" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sapphirinus">Eulonchus sapphirinus</taxonomicName>
adults have been observed exhibiting strong fidelity to a single flowering plant species, suggesting their role as important pollinators (
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, CJ" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="25" pageNumber="128" pagination="250 - 256" title="Flower-visiting and mating behaviour of Eulonchussapphirinus (Diptera: Acroceridae)." url="10.4039/n07-060" volume="140" year="2008 a">Borkent and Schlinger 2008a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="118" type="biology_ecology">
